To find the rank of matrix A, we need to perform Gaussian elimination to find the row echelon form of the matrix and then count the number of non-zero rows.

Matrix A:
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & -1 \\
2 & 3 & 1 \\
3 & 5 & 0 \\
\end{pmatrix}

Step 1: Subtract 2 times the first row from the second row, and subtract 3 times the first row from the third row.

\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & -1 \\
0 & -1 & 3 \\
0 & -1 & 3 \\
\end{pmatrix}

Step 2: Multiply the second row by -1 to make the leading entry positive.

\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & -1 \\
0 & 1 & -3 \\
0 & -1 & 3 \\
\end{pmatrix}

Step 3: Add the second row to the third row.

\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 & -1 \\
0 & 1 & -3 \\
0 & 0 & 0 \\
\end{pmatrix}

Now we have the row echelon form of matrix A. There are 2 non-zero rows, so the rank of matrix A is 2.
